# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cbor-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Amongst other uses, it is the recommended data serialization layer for the CoAP Internet of Things protocol suite and the data format on which COSE messages are based.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] It is also used in the Client-to-Authenticator Protocol (CTAP) within the scope of the FIDO2 project.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] CBOR was inspired by MessagePack, which was developed and promoted by Sadayuki Furuhashi.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] CBOR extended MessagePack, particularly by allowing to distinguish text strings from byte strings, which was implemented in 2013 in MessagePack.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] CBOR encoded data is seen as a stream of data items.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Each data item consists of a header byte containing a 3-bit type and 5-bit short count.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] This is followed by an optional extended count (if the short count is in the range 24–27), and an optional payload.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] For types 0, 1, and 7, there is no payload; the count *is* the value.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] For types 2 (byte string) and 3 (text string), the count is the length of the payload.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] For types 4 (array) and 5 (map), the count is the number of items (pairs) in the payload.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] For type 6 (tag), the payload is a single item and the count is a numeric tag number which describes the enclosed item.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Each data item's behaviour is defined by the major type and count.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The major type is used for selecting the main behaviour or type of each data item.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The 5-bit short count field encodes counts 0–23 directly.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Short counts of 24–27 indicate the count value is in a following 8, 16, 32 or 64-bit extended count field.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Values 28–30 are not assigned and must not be used.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Types are divided into "atomic" types 0–1 and 6–7, for which the count field encodes the value directly, and non-atomic types 2–5, for which the count field encodes the size of the following payload field.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] A short count of 31 is used with non-atomic types 2–5 to indicate an indefinite length; the payload is the following items until a "break" marker byte of 255 (type=7, short count=31).
[src:cbor-format/cbor] A short count of 31 is not permitted with the other atomic types 0, 1 or 6.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Type 6 (tag) is unusual in that its count field encodes a value directly, but also has a payload field (which always consists of a single item).
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Extended counts, and all multi-byte values, are encoded in network (big-endian) byte order.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] For integers, the count field *is* the value; there is no payload.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Type 0 encodes positive or unsigned integers, with values up to 264−1.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Type 1 encodes negative integers, with a value of −1−count, for values from −264 to −1.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Types 2 and 3 have a count field which encodes the length in bytes of the payload.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] A short count of 31 indicates an indefinite-length string.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] This is followed by zero or more definite-length strings of the same type, terminated by a "break" marker byte.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The value of the item is the concatenation of the values of the enclosed items.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Items of a different type, or nested indefinite-length strings, are not permitted.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Text strings must be individually well-formed; UTF-8 characters may not be split across items.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Type 4 has a count field encoding the number of following items, followed by that many items.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The items need not all be the same type; some programming languages call this a "tuple" rather than an "array".
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Alternatively, an indefinite-length encoding with a short count of 31 may be used.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] This continues until a "break" marker byte of 255.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Because nested items may also use the indefinite encoding, the parser must pair the break markers with the corresponding indefinite-length header bytes.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Type 5 is similar but encodes a map (also called a dictionary, or associative array) of key/value pairs.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] In this case, the count encodes the number of *pairs* of items.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] If the indefinite-length encoding is used, there must be an even number of items before the "break" marker byte.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] A semantic tag is another atomic type for which the count is the value, but it also has a payload (a single following item), and the two are considered one item in e.g. an array or a map.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The tag number provides additional type information for the following item, beyond what the 3-bit major type can provide.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] For example, a tag of 1 indicates that the following number is a Unix time value.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] A tag of 2 indicates that the following byte string encodes an unsigned bignum.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] A tag of 32 indicates that the following text string is a URI as defined in RFC 3986.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] RFC 8746 defines tags 64–87 to encode homogeneous arrays of fixed-size integer or floating-point values as byte strings.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The tag 55799 is allocated to mean "CBOR data follows".
[src:cbor-format/cbor] This is a semantic no-op, but allows the corresponding tag bytes `d9 d9 f7` to be prepended to a CBOR file without affecting its meaning.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] These bytes may be used as a "magic number" to distinguish the beginning of CBOR data.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The all-ones tag values 0xffff, 0xffffffff and 0xffffffffffffffff are reserved to indicate the absence of a tag in a CBOR decoding library; they should never appear in a data stream.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The break marker pseudo-item may not be the payload of a tag.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] This major type is used to encode various special values that do not fit into the other categories.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] It follows the same encoding-size rules as the other atomic types (0, 1, and 6), but the count field is interpreted differently.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The values 20–23 are used to encode the special values `false`, `true`, `null`, and `undefined`.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] A short count of 24 indicates a 1-byte extended count follows which can be used in future to encode additional special values.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] To simplify decoding, the values 0–31 may not be encoded in this form.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] None of the values 32–255 are currently defined.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Short counts of 25, 26 or 27 indicate a following extended count field is to be interpreted as a (big-endian) 16-, 32- or 64-bit IEEE floating point value.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] These are the same sizes as an extended count, but are interpreted differently.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] In particular, for all other major types, a 2-byte extended count of 0x1234 and a 4-byte extended count of 0x00001234 are exactly equivalent.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] This is not the case for floating-point values.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Short counts 28–30 are reserved, like for all other major types.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] A short count of 31 encodes the special "break" marker which terminates an indefinite-length encoding.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] This is related to, but different from, the use with other major types where a short count of 31 *begins* an indefinite length encoding.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] This is not an item, and may not appear in a defined-length payload.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] IANA has created the CBOR tags registry, located at https://www.iana.org/assignments/cbor-tags/cbor-tags.xhtml .
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Registrations must contain the template outlined below.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The **DAG-CBOR** specification is a stricter subset of CBOR, developed by Protocol Labs.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The problem that DAG-CBOR solves is that, in CBOR, an object can be serialized in more than one way.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] This means that one object can have two different serializations.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The DAG-CBOR specification uniquely picks a single CBOR representation, out of all possible CBOR representations of an object.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Some objects that can have a CBOR representation no longer has a DAG-CBOR representation, because their nature does not allow for a unique representation.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] For example, an indefinite-length items (can be a string, byte sequence, list, and map) does not have a DAG-CBOR representation, even though it can have a CBOR representation.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The DAG-CBOR specification allows consistent content-addressable storage.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] Specifically, a piece of data can be uniquely serialized as a sequence of bytes, and this sequence can then be hashed as its CID (content ID), usable for content-addressing.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] The name "DAG" denotes "directed acyclic graph", since the specification was produced specifically to allow for data objects in the form of Merkle DAGs.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] A **CBOR Web Token** (**CWT**) is a signed token that uses CBOR as the serialization format.
[src:cbor-format/cbor] They are an alternative to JSON Web Tokens (JWTs).
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Early character encodings that originated with optical or electrical telegraphy and in early computers could only represent a subset of the characters used in languages, sometimes restricted to upper case letters, numerals and limited punctuation.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Over time, encodings capable of representing more characters were created, such as ASCII, ISO/IEC 8859, and Unicode encodings such as UTF-8 and UTF-16.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The most popular character encoding on the World Wide Web is UTF-8, which is used in 98.9% of surveyed web sites, as of January 2026.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] In application programs and operating system tasks, both UTF-8 and UTF-16 are popular options.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The history of character codes illustrates the evolving need for machine-mediated character-based symbolic information over a distance, using once-novel electrical means.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The earliest codes were based upon manual and hand-written encoding and cyphering systems, such as Bacon's cipher, Braille, international maritime signal flags, and the 4-digit encoding of Chinese characters for a Chinese telegraph code (Hans Schjellerup, 1869).
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] With the adoption of electrical and electro-mechanical techniques these earliest codes were adapted to the new capabilities and limitations of the early machines.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The earliest well-known electrically transmitted character code, Morse code, introduced in the 1840s, used a system of four "symbols" (short signal, long signal, short space, long space) to generate codes of variable length.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Though some commercial use of Morse code was via machinery, it was often used as a manual code, generated by hand on a telegraph key and decipherable by ear, and persists in amateur radio and aeronautical use.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Most codes are of fixed per-character length or variable-length sequences of fixed-length codes (e.g.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Common examples of character encoding systems include Morse code, the Baudot code, the American Standard Code for Information Interchange (ASCII) and Unicode.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Unicode, a well-defined and extensible encoding system, has replaced most earlier character encodings, but the path of code development to the present is fairly well known.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The Baudot code, a five-bit encoding, was created by Émile Baudot in 1870, patented in 1874, modified by Donald Murray in 1901, and standardized by CCITT as International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The name *baudot* has been erroneously applied to ITA2 and its many variants.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] ITA2 suffered from many shortcomings and was often improved by many equipment manufacturers, sometimes creating compatibility issues.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Herman Hollerith invented punch card data encoding in the late 19th century to analyze census data.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Initially, each hole position represented a different data element, but later, numeric information was encoded by numbering the lower rows 0 to 9, with a punch in a column representing its row number.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Later alphabetic data was encoded by allowing more than one punch per column.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Electromechanical tabulating machines represented date internally by the timing of pulses relative to the motion of the cards through the machine.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] When IBM went to electronic processing, starting with the IBM 603 Electronic Multiplier, it used a variety of binary encoding schemes that were tied to the punch card code.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] IBM used several binary-coded decimal (BCD) six-bit character encoding schemes, starting as early as 1953 in its 702 and 704 computers, and in its later 7000 Series and 1400 series, as well as in associated peripherals.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Since the punched card code then in use was limited to digits, upper-case English letters and a few special characters, six bits were sufficient.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] These BCD encodings extended existing simple four-bit numeric encoding to include alphabetic and special characters, mapping them easily to punch-card encoding which was already in widespread use.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] IBM's codes were used primarily with IBM equipment.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Other computer vendors of the era had their own character codes, often six-bit, such as the encoding used by the UNIVAC I.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] They usually had the ability to read tapes produced on IBM equipment.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] IBM's BCD encodings were the precursors of their Extended Binary-Coded Decimal Interchange Code (usually abbreviated as EBCDIC), an eight-bit encoding scheme developed in 1963 for the IBM System/360 that featured a larger character set, including lower case letters.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] In 1959, the U.S. military defined its Fieldata code, a six-or seven-bit code, introduced by the U.S.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] While Fieldata addressed many of the then-modern issues (e.g. letter and digit codes arranged for machine collation), it fell short of its goals and was short-lived.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] In 1963 the first ASCII code was released (X3.4-1963) by the ASCII committee (which contained at least one member of the Fieldata committee, W.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Leubbert), which addressed most of the shortcomings of Fieldata, using a simpler seven-bit code.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Many of the changes were subtle, such as collatable character sets within certain numeric ranges.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] ASCII63 was a success, widely adopted by industry, and with the follow-up issue of the 1967 ASCII code (which added lower-case letters and fixed some "control code" issues) ASCII67 was adopted fairly widely.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] ASCII67's American-centric nature was somewhat addressed in the European ECMA-6 standard.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Eight-bit extended ASCII encodings, such as various vendor extensions and the ISO/IEC 8859 series, supported all ASCII characters as well as additional non-ASCII characters.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] In 1985, the average personal computer user's hard disk drive could store only about 10 megabytes, and it cost approximately US$250 on the wholesale market (and much higher if purchased separately at retail), so it was very important at the time to make every bit count.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The compromise solution that was eventually found and developed into Unicode was to break the assumption (dating back to telegraph codes) that each character should always directly correspond to a particular sequence of bits.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Instead, characters would first be mapped to a universal intermediate representation in the form of abstract numbers called code points.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Code points would then be represented in a variety of ways and with various default numbers of bits per character (code units) depending on context.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] To encode code points higher than the length of the code unit, such as above 256 for eight-bit units, the solution was to implement variable-length encodings where an escape sequence would signal that subsequent bits should be parsed as a higher code point.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The various terms related to character encoding are often used inconsistently or incorrectly.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Historically, the same standard would specify a repertoire of characters and how they were to be encoded into a stream of code units – usually with a single character per code unit.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] However, due to the emergence of more sophisticated character encodings, the distinction between terms has become important.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] A character is the smallest unit of text that has semantic value.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] In linguistics, this is called a grapheme and each of the various ways it may be written are called glyphs.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] What constitutes a character varies between character encodings.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] For example, for letters with diacritics, there are two distinct approaches that can be taken to encode them.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] They can be encoded either as a single unified character (known as a precomposed character), or as separate characters that combine into a single glyph.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The former simplifies the text handling system, but the latter allows any letter/diacritic combination to be used in text.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Some writing systems, such as Arabic and Hebrew, have graphemes whose shape and joining depend on context.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] A character set is a collection of characters used to represent text.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] For example, the Latin alphabet and Greek alphabet are character sets.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] A coded character set is a character set with each item uniquely mapped to a numberic value.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] This is also known as a code page, although that term is generally antiquated.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Originally, *code page* referred to a page number in an IBM manual that defined a particular character encoding.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Other vendors, including Microsoft, SAP, and Oracle Corporation, also published their own code pages, including notable Windows code page and code page 437.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Despite no longer referring to specific pages in a manual, many character encodings are still identified to by the same number.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Likewise, the term *code page* is still used to refer to character encoding.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] In Unix and Unix-like systems, the term *charmap* is commonly used; usually in the larger context of locales.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] IBM's Character Data Representation Architecture (CDRA) designates each entity with a coded character set identifier (CCSID), which is variously called a *charset*, *character set*, *code page*, or *CHARMAP*.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] A character repertoire is a set of characters that can be represented by a particular coded character set.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The repertoire may be closed, meaning that no additions are allowed without creating a new standard (as is the case with ASCII and most of the ISO-8859 series); or it may be open, allowing additions (as is the case with Unicode and to a limited extent Windows code pages).
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] A code point is the value or position of a character in a coded character set.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] A code point is represented by a sequence of code units.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Code space is the range of numerical values spanned by a coded character set.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] A code unit is the minimum bit combination that can represent a character in a character encoding (in computer science terms, it is the word size of the character encoding).
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Common code units include 7-bit, 8-bit, 16-bit, and 32-bit.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] In some encodings, some characters are encoded as multiple code units.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Unicode and its parallel standard, the ISO/IEC 10646 Universal Character Set, together constitute a unified standard for character encoding.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The purpose of this decomposition is to establish a universal set of characters that can be encoded in a variety of ways.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] To describe the model precisely, Unicode uses existing terms and defines new terms.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] An abstract character repertoire (ACR) is the full set of abstract characters that a system supports.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Unicode has an open repertoire, meaning that new characters will be added to the repertoire over time.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] A coded character set (CCS) is a function that maps characters to *code points* (each code point represents one character).
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] For example, in a given repertoire, the capital letter "A" in the Latin alphabet might be represented by the code point 65, the character "B" by 66, and so on.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Multiple coded character sets may share the same character repertoire; for example ISO/IEC 8859-1 and IBM code pages 037 and 500 all cover the same repertoire but map them to different code points.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Hardware and software systems typically have a maximum "native" word length, such as 16 or 32 bits.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] A character encoding may define code points whose length exceeds a system's native word length.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] *A character encoding form* (CEF) is the mapping of code points to *code units* that break up a code point in a standardized way so that each code unit fits within the system's word length.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] For example, a computer that represents numbers in 16-bit units can only represent code points up to 65,535 per unit, but larger code points can be represented using multiple 16-bit units as defined by the CEF.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] A character encoding scheme (CES) is the mapping of code units to a sequence of octets to facilitate storage on an octet-based file system or transmission over an octet-based network.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] See comparison of Unicode encodings for a detailed discussion.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] There may be a higher-level protocol which supplies additional information to select the particular variant of a Unicode character, particularly where there are regional variants that have been 'unified' in Unicode as the same character.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] An example is the XML attribute xml:lang.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The Unicode model uses the term "character map" for other systems which directly assign a sequence of characters to a sequence of bytes, covering all of the CCS, CEF and CES layers.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] A character is commonly documented as 'U+' followed by its code point value in hexadecimal.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The range of valid code points (the code space) for the Unicode standard is U+0000 to U+10FFFF, inclusive, divided in 17 planes, identified by the numbers 0 to 16.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Characters in the range U+0000 to U+FFFF are in plane 0, called the Basic Multilingual Plane (BMP).
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] This plane contains the most commonly used characters.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Characters in the range U+10000 to U+10FFFF in the other planes are called supplementary characters.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Consider, "ab̲c𐐀" – a string containing a Unicode combining character (U+0332 ◌̲ COMBINING LOW LINE to underline the ⟨b⟩) as well as a supplementary character (U+10400 𐐀 DESERET CAPITAL LETTER LONG I).
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Note in particular that 𐐀 is represented with either one 32-bit value (UTF-32), two 16-bit values (UTF-16), or four 8-bit values (UTF-8).
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] Although each of those forms uses the same total number of bits (32) to represent the grapheme, it is not obvious how the actual numeric byte values are related.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] To support environments using multiple character encodings, software has been developed to translate text between character encoding schemes, a process known as transcoding.
[src:cbor-format/character-encoding] The most used character encoding on the web is UTF-8, used in 98.9% of surveyed web sites, as of January 2026.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] This is a **comparison of data serialization formats**, various ways to convert complex objects to sequences of bits.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] It does not include markup languages used exclusively as document file formats.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The "classic" format is plain text, and an XML format is also supported.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**Theoretically possible due to abstraction, but no implementation is included.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The primary format is binary, but text and JSON formats are available.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**Means that generic tools/libraries know how to encode, decode, and dereference a reference to another piece of data in the same document.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] A tool may require the IDL file, but no more.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] Excludes custom, non-standardized referencing techniques.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**ASN.1 has X.681 (Information Object System), X.682 (Constraints), and X.683 (Parameterization) that allow for the precise specification of open types where the types of values can be identified by integers, by OIDs, etc.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] OIDs are a standard format for globally unique identifiers, as well as a standard notation ("absolute reference") for referencing a component of a value.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] For example, PKIX uses such notation in RFC 5912.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] With such notation (constraints on parameterized types using information object sets), generic ASN.1 tools/libraries can automatically encode/decode/resolve references within a document.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The primary format is binary, a json encoder is available.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The primary format is binary, but a text format is available.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The RFC CSV specification only deals with delimiters, newlines, and quote characters; it does not directly deal with serializing programming data structures.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The netstrings specification only deals with nested byte strings; anything else is outside the scope of the specification.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**PHP will unserialize any floating-point number correctly, but will serialize them to their full decimal expansion.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**XML data bindings and SOAP serialization tools provide type-safe XML serialization of programming data structures into XML.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] Shown are XML values that can be placed in XML elements and attributes.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**This syntax is not compatible with the Internet-Draft, but is used by some dialects of Lisp.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] All basic Ion types have a null variant, as its 0xXf tag.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] Any tag beginning with 0x0X other than 0x0f defines ignored padding.
[src:cbor-format/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] Interpretation of Netstrings is entirely application- or schema-dependent.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] For large volume scientific datasets, such as satellite data and output of numerical climate, weather, or ocean models, specific binary serialization standards have been developed, e.g.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] (There is a flag to marshal the code position of a function but it can only be unmarshalled in exactly the same program).
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The standard marshalling functions can preserve sharing and handle cyclic data, which can be configured by a flag.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:cbor-format/data-serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A programming language consists of a system of allowed sequences of symbols (constructs) together with rules that define how each construct is interpreted.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, a language might allow expressions representing various types of data, expressions that provide structuring rules for data, expressions representing various operations on data, and constructs that provide sequencing rules for the order in which to perform operations.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A simple type system for a programming language is a set of rules that associates a *data type* (for example, integer, floating point, string) with each *term* (data-valued expression) in a computer program.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In more ambitious type systems, a variety of constructs, such as variables, expressions, functions, and modules, may be assigned types.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Type systems formalize and enforce the otherwise implicit categories the programmer uses for algebraic data types, data structures, or other data types, such as "string", "array of float", "function returning boolean".
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The main purpose of a type system in a programming language is to reduce possibilities for bugs in computer programs due to mismatches in how values are interpreted in different parts of a program.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The aim is to prevent operations expecting a certain kind of value from being applied to values for which that operation does not make sense (validity errors).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A type system can detect and prevent some of these mismatches.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] When a type mismatch is detected, it is called a type error.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The type of a term constrains the contexts in which it may be used.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For a variable, the type system determines the allowed values of that variable.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For that variable to be presented as a parameter to an operation, the operation must be able to accept in that parameter any value that the type of the variable allows.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Type systems are typically specified as part of programming language design.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] They are built into interpreters and compilers for the language.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In some languages, the type system can be extended by optional tools that perform added checks using the language's original type syntax and grammar.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Type systems allow defining interfaces between different parts of a computer program, and then checking that the parts have been connected in a consistent way.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This checking can happen statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime), or as a combination of both.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Type systems have other purposes as well, such as expressing business rules, enabling certain compiler optimizations, allowing for multiple dispatch, and providing a form of documentation.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] An example of a simple type system is that of the C language.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The portions of a C program are the function definitions.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] One function is invoked by another function.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The interface of a function states the name of the function and a list of parameters that are passed to the function's code.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The code of an invoking function states the name of the invoked, along with the names of variables that hold values to pass to it.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] During a computer program's execution, the values are placed into temporary storage, then execution jumps to the code of the invoked function.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The invoked function's code accesses the values and makes use of them.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] If the instructions inside the function are written with the assumption of receiving an integer value, but the calling code passed a floating-point value, then the wrong result will be computed by the invoked function.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The C compiler checks the types of the arguments passed to a function when it is called against the types of the parameters declared in the function's definition.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] If the types do not match, the compiler throws a compile-time error or warning.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A compiler may also use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In many C compilers the *float* data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The depth of type constraints and the manner of their evaluation affect the *typing* of the language.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A programming language may further associate an operation with various resolutions for each type, in the case of type polymorphism.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Type theory is the study of type systems.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The concrete types of some programming languages, such as integers and strings, depend on practical issues of computer architecture, compiler implementation, and language design.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Formally, type theory studies type systems.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A programming language must have the opportunity to type check using the *type system* whether at compile time or runtime, manually annotated or automatically inferred.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Assigning a data type, termed *typing*, gives meaning to a sequence of bits such as a value in memory or some object such as a variable.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Associating a sequence of bits with a type conveys that meaning to the programmable hardware to form a *symbolic system* composed of that hardware and some program.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A program associates each value with at least one specific type, but it also can occur that one value is associated with many subtypes.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Other entities, such as objects, modules, communication channels, and dependencies can become associated with a type.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Even a type can become associated with a type.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] An implementation of a *type system* could in theory associate identifications called *data type* (a type of a value), *class* (a type of an object), and *kind* (a *type of a type*, or metatype).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] These are the abstractions that typing can go through, on a hierarchy of levels contained in a system.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] It is challenging to find a sufficiently expressive type system that satisfies all programming practices in a type safe manner.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A programming language compiler can also implement a *dependent type* or an *effect system*, which enables even more program specifications to be verified by a type checker.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Beyond simple value-type pairs, a virtual "region" of code is associated with an "effect" component describing *what* is being done *with what*, and enabling for example to "throw" an error report.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Thus the symbolic system may be a *type and effect system*, which endows it with more safety checking than type checking alone.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Whether automated by the compiler or specified by a programmer, a type system renders program behavior illegal if it falls outside the type-system rules.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A type error occurs when an operation receives a different type of data than it expected.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, a type error would happen if a line of code divides two integers, and is passed a string of letters instead of an integer.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] It is an unintended condition which might manifest in multiple stages of a program's development.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Thus a facility for detection of the error is needed in the type system.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In some languages, such as Haskell, for which type inference is automated, lint might be available to its compiler to aid in the detection of error.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Type safety contributes to program correctness, but might only guarantee correctness at the cost of making the type checking itself an undecidable problem (as in the halting problem).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In a *type system* with automated type checking, a program may prove to run incorrectly yet produce no compiler errors.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Division by zero is an unsafe and incorrect operation, but a type checker which only runs at compile time does not scan for division by zero in most languages; that division would surface as a runtime error.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] To prove the absence of these defects, other kinds of formal methods, collectively known as program analyses, are in common use.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Alternatively, a sufficiently expressive type system, such as in dependently typed languages, can prevent these kinds of errors (for example, expressing *the type of non-zero numbers*).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In addition, software testing is an empirical method for finding errors that such a type checker would not detect.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The process of verifying and enforcing the constraints of types, *type checking*, may occur at compile time (a static check) or at runtime (a dynamic check).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] If a language specification requires its typing rules strongly, more or less allowing only those automatic type conversions that do not lose information, one can refer to the process as *strongly typed*; if not, as *weakly typed*.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The terms are not usually used in a strict sense.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Even if the expression `<complex test>` always evaluates to `true` at runtime, most type checkers will reject the program as ill-typed, because it is difficult (if not impossible) for a static analyzer to determine that the `else` branch will not be taken.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, historically C# declares variables statically, but C# 4.0 introduces the `dynamic` keyword, which is used to declare variables to be checked dynamically at runtime.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, Java and some other ostensibly statically typed languages support downcasting types to their subtypes, querying an object to discover its dynamic type and other type operations that depend on runtime type information.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] More generally, most programming languages include mechanisms for dispatching over different 'kinds' of data, such as disjoint unions, runtime polymorphism, and variant types.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Even when not interacting with type annotations or type checking, such mechanisms are materially similar to dynamic typing implementations.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Objects in object-oriented languages are usually accessed by a reference whose static target type (or manifest type) is equal to either the object's runtime type (its latent type) or a supertype thereof.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This is conformant with the Liskov substitution principle, which states that all operations performed on an instance of a given type can also be performed on an instance of a subtype.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This concept is also known as subsumption or subtype polymorphism.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In some languages subtypes may also possess covariant or contravariant return types and argument types respectively.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Certain languages, for example Clojure, Common Lisp, or Cython are dynamically type checked by default, but allow programs to opt into static type checking by providing optional annotations.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] One reason to use such hints would be to optimize the performance of critical sections of a program.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The programming environment *DrRacket*, a pedagogic environment based on Lisp, and a precursor of the language Racket is also soft-typed.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Conversely, as of version 4.0, the C# language provides a way to indicate that a variable should not be statically type checked.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A variable whose type is `dynamic` will not be subject to static type checking.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Instead, the program relies on runtime type information to determine how the variable may be used.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In Rust, the `dyn std::any::Any` trait object provides dynamic typing of types containing no or only `'static` lifetimes.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The choice between static and dynamic typing requires certain trade-offs.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Static typing can find type errors reliably at compile time, which increases the reliability of the delivered program.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] However, programmers disagree over how commonly type errors occur, resulting in further disagreements over the proportion of those bugs that are coded that would be caught by appropriately representing the designed types in code.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Static typing advocates believe programs are more reliable when they have been well type-checked, whereas dynamic-typing advocates point to distributed code that has proven reliable and to small bug databases.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The value of static typing increases as the strength of the type system is increased.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Advocates of dependent typing, implemented in languages such as Dependent ML and Epigram, have suggested that almost all bugs can be considered type errors, if the types used in a program are properly declared by the programmer or correctly inferred by the compiler.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Static typing usually results in compiled code that executes faster.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] When the compiler knows the exact data types that are in use (which is necessary for static verification, either through declaration or inference) it can produce optimized machine code.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Some dynamically typed languages such as Common Lisp allow optional type declarations for optimization for this reason.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] By contrast, dynamic typing may allow compilers to run faster and interpreters to dynamically load new code, because changes to source code in dynamically typed languages may result in less checking to perform and less code to revisit.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This too may reduce the edit-compile-test-debug cycle.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Statically typed languages that lack type inference (such as C and Java prior to version 10) require that programmers declare the types that a method or function must use.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This can serve as added program documentation, that is active and dynamic, instead of static.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This allows a compiler to prevent it from drifting out of synchrony, and from being ignored by programmers.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] However, a language can be statically typed without requiring type declarations (examples include Haskell, Scala, OCaml, F#, Swift, and to a lesser extent C# and C++), so explicit type declaration is not required for static typing in all languages.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Dynamic typing allows constructs that some (simple) static type checking would reject as illegal.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, *eval* functions, which execute arbitrary data as code, become possible.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] An *eval* function is possible with static typing, but requires advanced uses of algebraic data types.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Further, dynamic typing better accommodates transitional code and prototyping, such as allowing a placeholder data structure (mock object) to be transparently used in place of a full data structure (usually for the purposes of experimentation and testing).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Dynamic typing typically allows duck typing (which enables easier code reuse).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Many languages with static typing also feature duck typing or other mechanisms like generic programming that also enable easier code reuse.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Dynamic typing typically makes metaprogramming easier to use.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, C++ templates are typically more cumbersome to write than the equivalent Ruby or Python code since C++ has stronger rules regarding type definitions (for both functions and variables).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This forces a developer to write more boilerplate code for a template than a Python developer would need to.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] More advanced runtime constructs such as metaclasses and introspection are often harder to use in statically typed languages.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In some languages, such features may also be used e.g. to generate new types and behaviors on the fly, based on runtime data.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Such advanced constructs are often provided by dynamic programming languages; many of these are dynamically typed, although *dynamic typing* need not be related to *dynamic programming languages*.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Languages are often colloquially referred to as *strongly typed* or *weakly typed*.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In fact, there is no universally accepted definition of what these terms mean.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In general, there are more precise terms to represent the differences between type systems that lead people to call them "strong" or "weak".
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A third way of categorizing the type system of a programming language is by the safety of typed operations and conversions.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *type-safe language* to describe languages that do not allow operations or conversions that violate the rules of the type system.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *memory-safe language* (or just *safe language*) to describe languages that do not allow programs to access memory that has not been assigned for their use.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, a memory-safe language will check array bounds, or else statically guarantee (i.e., at compile time before execution) that array accesses out of the array boundaries will cause compile-time and perhaps runtime errors.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In this example, the variable `z` will have the value 42.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Although this may not be what the programmer anticipated, it is a well-defined result.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] If `y` were a different string, one that could not be converted to a number (e.g., "Hello, World"), the result would be well-defined also.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A program can be type-safe or memory-safe and still crash on an invalid operation.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This is for languages where the type system is not sufficiently advanced to precisely specify the validity of operations on all possible operands.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] But if a program encounters an operation that is not type-safe, terminating the program is often the only option.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In this example `z` will point to a memory address five characters beyond `y`, equivalent to three characters after the terminating zero character of the string pointed to by `y`.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This is memory that the program is not expected to access.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In C terms this is simply undefined behaviour and the program may do anything; with a simple compiler it might actually print whatever byte is stored after the string "37".
[src:cbor-format/type-system] As this example shows, C is not memory-safe.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] As arbitrary data was assumed to be a character, it is also not a type-safe language.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In general, type-safety and memory-safety go hand in hand.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, a language that supports pointer arithmetic and number-to-pointer conversions (like C) is neither memory-safe nor type-safe, because it allows arbitrary memory to be accessed as if it were valid memory of any type.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Some languages allow different levels of checking to apply to different regions of code.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Additional tools such as lint and IBM Rational Purify can also be used to achieve a higher level of strictness.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] It has been proposed, chiefly by Gilad Bracha, that the choice of type system be made independent of choice of language; that a type system should be a module that can be *plugged* into a language as needed.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] He believes this is advantageous, because what he calls mandatory type systems make languages less expressive and code more fragile.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The requirement that the type system does not affect the semantics of the language is difficult to fulfill.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Optional typing is related to, but distinct from, gradual typing.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] While both typing disciplines can be used to perform static analysis of code (static typing), optional type systems do not enforce type safety at runtime (dynamic typing).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The type-theoretic foundations of polymorphism are closely related to those of abstraction, modularity and (in some cases) subtyping.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Many type systems have been created that are specialized for use in certain environments with certain types of data, or for out-of-band static program analysis.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Frequently, these are based on ideas from formal type theory and are only available as part of prototype research systems.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The following table gives an overview over type theoretic concepts that are used in specialized type systems.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The names M, N, O range over terms and the names $\sigma ,\tau$ range over types.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Also referred to as *dependent sum type*, since ${\textstyle (x:\sigma )\times \tau =\sum _{x:\sigma }\tau }$ .
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Dependent types are based on the idea of using scalars or values to more precisely describe the type of some other value.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, $\mathrm {matrix} (3,3)$ might be the type of a $3\times 3$ matrix.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] where k, m, n are arbitrary positive integer values.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A variant of ML called Dependent ML has been created based on this type system, but because type checking for conventional dependent types is undecidable, not all programs using them can be type-checked without some kind of limits.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Dependent ML limits the sort of equality it can decide to Presburger arithmetic.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Other languages such as Epigram make the value of all expressions in the language decidable so that type checking can be decidable.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] However, in general proof of decidability is undecidable, so many programs require hand-written annotations that may be very non-trivial.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] As this impedes the development process, many language implementations provide an easy way out in the form of an option to disable this condition.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This, however, comes at the cost of making the type-checker run in an infinite loop when fed programs that do not type-check, causing the compilation to fail.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:cbor-format/type-system] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
